The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                              
	 Mumbai, July 19: Bombay High Court today said the 11 accused in the 2008 Malegaon blast case would be tried under the Maharashtra Control of Organised Crime Act (MCOCA).          
	A lower court had earlier dropped charges under the MCOCA against the accused, including Sadhvi Pragya Singh Thakur and a dismissed army officer.                   
	 New Delhi: The Supreme Court on Monday accepted former Chief Justice of India A.M. Ahmadis resignation from the post of chairman of the Bhopal Memorial Hospital Trust and allowed the Centre to take over its management. The trust will be wound up and the hospital will function under the Union atomic energy and biotechnology departments.                   
	 Calcutta: The Bengal government has asked the Centre to defer the tripartite talks with the Gorkha Janmukti Morcha. The talks are scheduled to be held on July 24. The Supreme Court has directed the Centre and the Bengal government to ensure that NH31, the road that links Sikkim with the rest of the country, is not blocked during the Morcha strike on July 25.                  
	 Calcutta: Bengal Congress chief Manas Bhuniya on Monday requested Sabitri Mitra, the Congress MLA from Maldas Araidanga, to reconsider her decision to quit the party and join the Trinamul Congress.                   
	 Midnapore: Police on Monday organised a football match in West Midnapores Lalgarh, in a move to wean away local youths from Maoists. Around 150 youths, including the son of arrested Peoples Committee against Police Atrocities leader Chhatradhar Mahato, participated in the event. Two youths , who were selected the best players of the tournament, will get a chance to train at German football club Bayern Munich, the police said.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): Lashkar-e-Toiba (LeT) operative David Headley has corroborated Ajmal Kasabs claim that the 26/11 terrorists got training in swimming and diving from the Pakistani navy. Headley has also told interrogators that the Pakistan intelligence agency ISI had paid Rs 25 lakh to the LeT to purchase a boat that the terrorists used to travel from Karachi to the Pakistani maritime boundary.                                                                                                                                              
